            <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/cws/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmintonsunday.livemint.com%2Fnews%2Findia-pakistan-cricket-dont-let-the-maniacs-play-spoilsport%2F2.3.4080358664.html" target="_blank" title="Follow us on Linkedin"class = "gplus-icon"></a>
            <a href="https://twitter.com/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmintonsunday.livemint.com%2Fnews%2Findia-pakistan-cricket-dont-let-the-maniacs-play-spoilsport%2F2.3.4080358664.html&text=India-Pakistan+cricket%3A+Don%27t+let+the+maniacs+play+spoilsport" target="_blank" title="Follow us on Twitter" class = "linkedin-icon"></a>
            <a target="_blank" href="//www.reddit.com/submit?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmintonsunday.livemint.com%2Fnews%2Findia-pakistan-cricket-dont-let-the-maniacs-play-spoilsport%2F2.3.4080358664.html&title=India-Pakistan+cricket%3A+Don%27t+let+the+maniacs+play+spoilsport"  class="reddit-icon" style="margin-right:20px !important;"></a>
            <a target="_blank" href="mailTo:Enter your friend email?subject=India-Pakistan cricket: Don't let the maniacs play spoilsport&body=Hi ,%0A%0APlease check this out %0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Fmintonsunday.livemint.com%2Fnews%2Findia-pakistan-cricket-dont-let-the-maniacs-play-spoilsport%2F2.3.4080358664.html" class="mail-icon" style="margin:0"></a>
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-12 col-lg-12 byLine">
                            <span> <a href="mailto:dilip@livemint.com?subject=India-Pakistan cricket: Don't let the maniacs play spoilsport&body=http://mintonsunday.livemint.com/news/india-pakistan-cricket-dont-let-the-maniacs-play-spoilsport/2.3.4080358664.html" class = "message-icon"></a>Dilip D'Souza</span>                         
                        </div>                        
                    </div> 
 <!--  end social icons -->                 	 <div class="row pa15">
                        <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-12">
								<div class="text" channel="BP Web,LiveMint" id="U2101160993004iXH"><br /><div class="p">When terrorists assaulted Mumbai in November 2008, I got a note from an old college friend I hadn&rsquo;t heard from in many months. &ldquo;Now don&rsquo;t start justifying what these guys are doing to India!&rdquo; he wrote.</div><br /><div class="p">I knew this had to do with his objections to my articles about such previous acts of terror as the 1984 massacre in Delhi, or the 1992-93 slaughter in Mumbai. Still, I was flabbergasted by this remark. So, I wrote back: &ldquo;When the terrorists manage to get friends who have known each other for over 30 years to mistrust each other enough to make remarks like this, they have succeeded beyond their wildest dreams.&rdquo;</div><br /><div class="p">I have been thinking about that little exchange after last Monday&rsquo;s assault on Gurdaspur. Seven killed, the terrorists holed up for several hours before being themselves killed, and when it&rsquo;s all over, what&rsquo;s one of the first things we hear? A BCCI official pronouncing that there will be no cricket with Pakistan until there&rsquo;s an end to terrorism. Many others, former India captain Sourav Ganguly included, endorse that statement.</div><br /><div class="p"><div class="row relatedStories"><h4>More from Play-by-Play</h4><div class="col-xs-6 col-sm-6 col-md-6"><div class="thumbnail"><a href="http://mintonsunday.livemint.com/news/the-ipl-mess-fellow-cricket-fans-the-joke-is-on-us/2.3.3760204044.html"><img src="http://www.livemint.com/r/LiveMint/Period1/2015/08/01/Photos/ipl-kSR--330x220@LiveMint.JPG"></a><div class="caption"><h2><a href="http://mintonsunday.livemint.com/news/the-ipl-mess-fellow-cricket-fans-the-joke-is-on-us/2.3.3760204044.html">The IPL mess: Fellow cricket fans, the joke is on us</a></h2></div></div></div></div><br /></div><br /><div class="p">And it occurs to me&mdash;when the terrorists manage to get this cricket-crazy country to put cricket tours on hold, they have succeeded way beyond their wildest dreams.</div><br /><div class="p">For that&rsquo;s what they want to see happen&mdash;two countries so mired in suspicion directed across their border that they cannot help but nurture hatreds within the border too. So mired in suspicion that even ordinary people voluntarily give up the one thing that appeals to people across the subcontinent&mdash;cricket. Terrorists want us all to wallow in hostility, because it makes their craven purposes easier to achieve. Like sheep, we fall into line. Ready to wallow.</div><br /><div class="p">Let me say it: I don&rsquo;t agree with the folks who say, again this week, that we should stop playing cricket with Pakistan because we believe there are terror attacks originating from there.</div><br /><div class="p">On the contrary, I think the greatest slap in the face for the terrorists&mdash;to hate-mongers on either side, really&mdash;would be for India and Pakistan to play even more cricket. Even more tennis. Even more badminton. Even more kabaddi. Even more whatever.</div><br /><div class="p">Because... well, consider just the history of cricket between our two countries. I will use the rest of this column to bring back memories of moments, players, nail-biting, all that.</div><br /><div class="p">Remember Bangalore, March 1987? It was Sunil Gavaskar&rsquo;s last Test, and it was against a Pakistan team featuring Javed Miandad, Imran Khan, Wasim Akram and Iqbal Qasim, among others. India lost narrowly. But Gavaskar produced the performance of the Test&mdash;a match-defining, soul-stirring 96 that is often still called his &ldquo;greatest effort in Tests&rdquo;. When Gavaskar was out, India had reached 180 in pursuit of 221 to win; that is, he had scored over half of India&rsquo;s runs. It was a &ldquo;match of riveting theatre&rdquo;, said <i>Wisden</i> in a line I haven&rsquo;t forgotten in over a quarter century; and on its last day, &ldquo;Gavaskar gave a masterly exhibition of technique and judgement.&rdquo;</div><br /><div class="p">Or remember Delhi, February 1999? All through my youth, I had marvelled at Jim Laker&rsquo;s remarkable feat, bowling for England against Australia in a 1956 Test. He took 10 wickets in an innings (and nine in the other). It seemed one of those once-in-a-lifetime performances that would never be repeated. But bowling in Delhi with skill and spirit, that modern Indian master Anil Kumble took down wicket after wicket as Pakistan crumbled while chasing 420. When an ecstatic V.V.S. Laxman leaned at short-leg to catch Pakistan&rsquo;s last man, Akram, Kumble had 10 in an innings too. And India had won by plenty. There were reports that the roiling crowd tore Kumble&rsquo;s shirt. Somehow, I doubt he objected.</div><br /><div class="p">Then there&rsquo;s the 1978 series in Pakistan, the first in nearly 18 years. During that gap, the neighbours fought two bitter wars and a third neighbour was born. India went into that Test series with their long-feared spin attack expected to carry their fortunes yet again. Which team, even today, would not give an arm and a leg to feature Bishan Singh Bedi, B.S. Chandrasekhar and E.A.S. Prasanna? But in truth, they were in decline and were cruelly exposed. Their spectacular failure in the face of sustained excellence from Zaheer Abbas&mdash;a double-century, a century and a 96&mdash;is something Indian fans still remember as the sunset of a great era. Prasanna took just two expensive wickets and never played for India again; Bedi and Chandrasekhar lasted only a handful of Tests more over the next several months.</div><br /><div class="p">And there&rsquo;s so much more. The 2004 series featured legions of delirious fans from both countries who painted both flags on their cheeks, Pakistani crowds that screamed &ldquo;Balaji, Balaji&rdquo; at India&rsquo;s charismatic and always-smiling fast bowler, and a rollicking partnership between Rahul Dravid and Mohammed Kaif to win the fourth ODI for India. The first-ever Test the countries played, in Delhi in October 1952, saw the great Vinoo Mankad take 13 wickets to crush Pakistan. Pakistan&rsquo;s superb fast-bowler, Fazal Mahmood, later wrote that Mankad &ldquo;tormented all our batsmen&rdquo; (Mahmood was the only one who didn&rsquo;t get out to Mankad) and &ldquo;often the ball came at us chest-high&rdquo;. Chest-high, from a slow spinner of the ball!</div><br /><div class="p"><div class="row relatedStories"><h4>More from Play-by-Play</h4><div class="col-xs-6 col-sm-6 col-md-6"><div class="thumbnail"><a href="http://mintonsunday.livemint.com/news/what-makes-a-sport-beautiful/2.3.3462348191.html"><img src="http://www.livemint.com/r/LiveMint/Period1/2015/08/01/Photos/sportbeaut-kSR--330x220@LiveMint.jpg"></a><div class="caption"><h2><a href="http://mintonsunday.livemint.com/news/what-makes-a-sport-beautiful/2.3.3462348191.html">What makes a sport beautiful?</a></h2></div></div></div></div><br /></div><br /><div class="p">And there&rsquo;s even more... but you get the idea. Plenty of intense, skilled, hard-fought cricket that enough players in both countries have also spoken of as some of their most satisfying moments in the game. Plenty over the decades to exhilarate fans of the sport.</div><br /><div class="p">Plenty to remind us that we don&rsquo;t need our existence in this part of the world to be constrained and strait-jacketed by murderous maniacs or hate-filled rabble-rousers. </div><br /><div class="p">That we must not, ever, let them win.</div><br /><div class="p"></div><br /><div class="p"><i>Once a computer scientist, Dilip D&rsquo;Souza now lives in Mumbai and writes for his dinners. His latest book is</i> Final Test: Exit Sachin Tendulkar.</div><br /><div class="p"><i>Twitter:</i> @DeathEndsFun</div><br /><div class="p"><i>Death Ends Fun:</i> http://dcubed.blogspot.com</div><br /><div class="p"><i>Comments are welcome at</i> feedback@livemint.com</div><br /><br /></div>	
                        </div>
